inlocks inside of them, and the smaller<br />spinlock *should* be able to result in smaller data structures.<br /><br />Of course, that assumes that they have been packed correctly. And they<br />seldom are ;(<br /><br />Looking at 'struct task_struct', for example, the spinlocks there<br />aren't next to each other, and have pointers and 'unsigned int's<br />around them, so rather than shrinking the data structure, it just<br />results in holes.<br /><br />                       Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
